        "content": "<p>While re-writing my lecture notes for my introductory proof course, I realised that no mathematician says, 'this follows by exact h', but we often say, 'this follows from h'.</p>\n<p>As the <code>from</code> tactic is synonymous to <code>exact</code>, I plan to us <code>from</code> everywhere. The only downside is that students might be confused by <code>exact</code> if they read mathlib. Any thoughts? Is this a good plan or a bad plan?</p>\n<p>I'm also veering more to teaching inductive proofs by pattern matching rather than the <code>induction</code> tactic.  Pattern matching does a cleaner job of announcing the cases and avoids needing to name the induction hypothesis. In this, it's closer to a tradition mathematical proof.</p>",
        "id": 248719578,
        "sender_full_name": "Gihan Marasingha",
        "timestamp": 1628347463
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Are you aware of <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib_docs/tactics.html#case\">tactic#case</a>, which allows you to announce the cases for <code>induction</code>?</p>",
        "id": 248726645,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1628357480
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Using pattern matching alone doesn't work very well if a proof starts the induction halfway through</p>",
        "id": 248726705,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1628357535
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks. I understand the deficiencies of proofs by pattern-matching, especially in Lean 3 and I will still be teaching the <code>induction</code> tactic for that very reason. Nonetheless, I feel that for students who have just encountered induction, a pattern-matching proof may be easier to understand. Of course, only experience will determine the truth of the matter.</p>\n<p>My arguments are two fold. First, a proof by pattern matching looks like (indeed is) a recursive construction. If students are taught recursion via pattern matching, then they may be more likely to understand induction as merely another example of recursion.</p>\n<p>Second was my point about the clarity of the argument, especially when the proof is presented non-interactively.</p>\n<p>To take an example, consider proving <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>n</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">0 + n = n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.72777em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span></span></span></span>, for every natural number <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span></span></span></span>. An informal proof might be:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Write <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P(n)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> for the statement <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>n</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">0 + n = n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.72777em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span></span></span></span>.  We prove <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∀</mi><mi>n</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>P</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\forall n, P(n)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∀</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> by induction.<br>\nBase case: <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mn>0</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P(0)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> is the assertion <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">0 + 0 = 0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.72777em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span></span></span></span>, which follows by reflexivity.<br>\nInductive step: we must show <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P(k + 1)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>, i.e. $$0 + (k + 1) = k + 1$  on the assumption <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>k</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P(k)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>, i.e. <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">0 + k = k</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.72777em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span></span></span></span>. Rewriting with the<br>\ndefinition of addition, we must show <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>k</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(0 + k) + 1 = k + 1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.77777em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span>. Rewriting with  <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>k</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P(k)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>, this is <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">k + 1 = k + 1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.77777em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.77777em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>This translates fairly directly into the following pattern-matching proof. The major difference here is that I'm not exclaiming, \"here's a proof by induction\". I'm also using <code>zero_add n</code> in place of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P(n)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kd\">lemma</span> <span class=\"n\">zero_add</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"bp\">∀</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">n</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"o\">),</span> <span class=\"mi\">0</span> <span class=\"bp\">+</span> <span class=\"n\">n</span> <span class=\"bp\">=</span> <span class=\"n\">n</span>\n  <span class=\"bp\">|</span> <span class=\"mi\">0</span>       <span class=\"o\">:=</span> <span class=\"n\">rfl</span>\n  <span class=\"bp\">|</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">k</span> <span class=\"bp\">+</span> <span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"o\">)</span> <span class=\"o\">:=</span> <span class=\"kd\">by</span> <span class=\"n\">rw</span> <span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">nat.add_succ</span><span class=\"o\">,</span> <span class=\"n\">zero_add</span> <span class=\"n\">k</span><span class=\"o\">]</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>A proof using the <code>induction</code> tactic has the advantage that it does, at least, use the word induction. Other than that, it doesn't look much like the hand-written proof. The names of the cases are the names of the constructors of <code>nat</code>, which is not likely to be how a new maths undergraduate thinks of induction. It's not so clear what <code>ih</code> refers to in the <code>succ</code> case, whereas the reference to <code>zero_add k</code> in the pattern-matching proof is quite explicit.</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kd\">lemma</span> <span class=\"n\">zero_add'</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">n</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"o\">)</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"mi\">0</span> <span class=\"bp\">+</span> <span class=\"n\">n</span> <span class=\"bp\">=</span> <span class=\"n\">n</span> <span class=\"o\">:=</span>\n<span class=\"kd\">begin</span>\n  <span class=\"n\">induction</span> <span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"o\">,</span>\n  <span class=\"n\">case</span> <span class=\"n\">zero</span> <span class=\"o\">{</span> <span class=\"n\">refl</span> <span class=\"o\">},</span>\n  <span class=\"n\">case</span> <span class=\"n\">succ</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">k</span> <span class=\"n\">ih</span> <span class=\"o\">{</span> <span class=\"n\">rw</span> <span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">nat.add_succ</span><span class=\"o\">,</span> <span class=\"n\">ih</span><span class=\"o\">]</span> <span class=\"o\">}</span>\n<span class=\"kd\">end</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
